# Annotation Property: schema1:titleEIDR (titleEIDR)

AnnotationAssertion(schema1:category schema1:titleEIDR "issue-2469")
AnnotationAssertion(schema1:domainIncludes schema1:titleEIDR schema1:Movie)
AnnotationAssertion(schema1:domainIncludes schema1:titleEIDR schema1:TVEpisode)
AnnotationAssertion(schema1:isPartOf schema1:titleEIDR <http://pending.schema.org>)
AnnotationAssertion(schema1:rangeIncludes schema1:titleEIDR schema1:Text)
AnnotationAssertion(schema1:rangeIncludes schema1:titleEIDR schema1:URL)
AnnotationAssertion(schema1:source schema1:titleEIDR <https://github.com/schemaorg/schemaorg/issues/2469>)
AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:comment schema1:titleEIDR "An <a href=\"https://eidr.org/\">EIDR</a> (Entertainment Identifier Registry) <a class=\"localLink\" href=\"http://schema.org/identifier\">identifier</a> representing at the most general/abstract level, a work of film or television.<br/><br/>

For example, the motion picture known as \"Ghostbusters\" has a titleEIDR of  \"10.5240/7EC7-228A-510A-053E-CBB8-J\". This title (or work) may have several variants, which EIDR calls \"edits\". See <a class=\"localLink\" href=\"http://schema.org/editEIDR\">editEIDR</a>.<br/><br/>

Since schema.org types like <a class=\"localLink\" href=\"http://schema.org/Movie\">Movie</a> and <a class=\"localLink\" href=\"http://schema.org/TVEpisode\">TVEpisode</a> can be used for both works and their multiple expressions, it is possible to use <a class=\"localLink\" href=\"http://schema.org/titleEIDR\">titleEIDR</a> alone (for a general description), or alongside <a class=\"localLink\" href=\"http://schema.org/editEIDR\">editEIDR</a> for a more edit-specific description.")
AnnotationAssertion(rdfs:label schema1:titleEIDR "titleEIDR")
SubAnnotationPropertyOf(schema1:titleEIDR schema1:identifier)

